-- APPENDIX A  --  THEME PHILOSOPHY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-- Each theme is hand-tuned around four values: Background, Sidebar,
-- Accent, and Text. The remaining channels (Element, ElementHover,
-- Border, etc.) are picked to keep contrast consistent across themes.
--
-- Ocean
--   Inspired by the calm of deep water at night. The accent is a
--   cool sky-blue that pops against the navy sidebar without being
--   harsh on dark screens. Best paired with marine icons.
--
-- Crimson
--   A bold, dramatic palette: near-black surfaces with an intense
--   red accent. Good for "danger" themed hubs or anything that
--   needs to feel high-stakes.
--
-- MatrixGreen
--   Classic cyberpunk-terminal vibe. The accent is a saturated
--   green that reads like CRT text. Best with monospace icons.
--
-- Amethyst
--   Royal purple on midnight. Feels expensive, slightly mystical.
--   Pairs well with magic/RPG hubs.
--
-- Sunset
--   Warm orange + red, like a golden hour overlay. Friendly and
--   inviting; great for casual / minigame UIs.
--
-- Midnight
--   Cool blue-grey, very low saturation. Reads as calm and
--   professional. Good for analytics dashboards.
--
-- Forest
--   Mossy greens and earth tones. Organic and grounded.
--
-- Cyber
--   Electric cyan accent on near-black, with a magenta error
--   highlight. Maximum neon, minimum apology.
--
-- Aurora
--   Mint + lilac on deep teal. Inspired by the northern lights.
--   Soft but distinctive.
--
-- Mono
--   Black and white. The accent is pure white. Use this when
--   you want the content to do the talking, not the chrome.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-- APPENDIX B  --  KEYBIND DESIGN NOTES
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-- Why a single library-wide toggle keybind (not one per window)?
--
--   1. Discoverability.  Users only need to remember ONE key to
--      get their UI back. With multiple windows it would be unclear
--      which one a keypress targeted.
--   2. Predictability.  External scripts can reliably call
--      Aquafield:Toggle() without knowing the structure.
--   3. Consistency with Rayfield.  Rayfield uses a single global
--      toggle keybind; we keep that contract.
--
-- Why default to "K"?
--
--   * It is unbound in default Roblox controls.
--   * It is easy to press with the left hand while moving with WASD.
--   * It matches the request in the project brief.
--
-- How is the keybind persisted?
--
--   When ConfigurationSaving is enabled, the keybind name is stored
--   under the _meta.keybind field of the JSON config.  On the next
--   :LoadConfiguration() call the keybind is restored before any
--   tab UI is rebuilt, so the user's preference takes effect
--   immediately.
--
-- How does the Settings tab keybind picker stay in sync?
--
--   The picker is a normal CreateKeybind() control. We poll its
--   CurrentKeybind in a background coroutine and update the
--   library's ToggleUIKeybind whenever it changes. This avoids
--   monkey-patching UserInputService.InputBegan.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-- APPENDIX C  --  PERFORMANCE NOTES
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-- The particle field is intentionally cheap: max 40 simultaneous
-- particles, each a 2-5px Frame with a Tween that runs once and
-- destroys itself. CPU cost is dominated by the Tween scheduler.
--
-- Theme switching does not rebuild any UI. It iterates the
-- _themed registry and re-assigns BackgroundColor3 / TextColor3 /
-- ImageColor3 / UIStroke.Color in place. The registry stores a
-- weak reference shape (table per instance) so deleted instances
-- become a no-op rather than throwing.
--
-- Config saving is debounced to once every 10 seconds by the
-- autosave loop. It is also called on window close. The data is
-- JSON-encoded with HttpService, which is faster than table.concat
-- for nested structures.
--
-- All Tweens use Quad-Out by default; the "spring" helper uses
-- Back-Out for entrance bounce. We deliberately avoid Elastic for
-- frequent interactions because it can feel sluggish.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-- APPENDIX D  --  MIGRATING FROM RAYFIELD
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-- Aquafield's public API is a strict superset of Rayfield's.
-- A Rayfield script generally just works by changing the
-- loadstring URL. Behavioural differences worth noting:
--
--   * Aquafield auto-injects a "Settings" tab. If you do not
--     want it, comment out the `do ... end` block at the bottom
--     of CreateWindow.
--   * The default toggle keybind is K. Rayfield uses K too,
--     so no change is needed.
--   * Themes are named differently and Aquafield ships with
--     ten of them. Pass Theme = "Default" to fall back to Ocean.
--   * Notifications include a subtle gradient overlay; pass
--     Image = your_id to keep parity with Rayfield calls.
--   * Window:Toggle() minimises the window (chrome-only).
--     Aquafield:Toggle() hides the entire UI (the keybind path).
